data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8.

**No migration is needed** for this code. It will compile and run as-is on .NET 8.

That said, a modern idiomatic improvement would be to replace raw threads with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.WhenAll`:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
    {
        await Task.Delay(100, ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    });
}
```

This gives you built-in cancellation support via `CancellationToken` if you need it later — the cooperative replacement for `Thread.Abort`.
